Today's loot (~2 buckets' load from each of us). Thanks @xytoh for wanting to do this together, braving the never-ending rain and long + early commute across the island! Found so many types of trash; to name a few: cigarette butts, plastic bags, styrofoam dabao boxes, used bottles and drink cans, surgical masks, gloves, hair ties, toy rubber balls, sweet wrappers, bbt tea cups with plastic bags, straw and chopstick wrappers, bullets used in Nerf guns, and more. On the way to the meet the best people in the world.

It‚Äôs been an annual tradition for us, every year our family will spend some time together at Chinatown for a good meal. Who says family reunion only happens during new year? Mid Autumn is the time for our ‚Äúannual‚Äù family reviews of which mooncake is the best, which bakwa is good this year, and after the meal we will go home with so many bags of calories. This is what I really love about this time of the year, it‚Äôs the gathering of the sweet-tooth family!..

Be enchanted by 700 sculptured lanterns along the streets of Chinatown. This is my story ‚Äì Heartfelt story of food delivery heroes captured during COVID19 Pandemic. Many of us have had the good fortune of working or staying at home during this pandemic with food delivered by these heroes. Their service has¬† allowed us to have better focus on our work or family care at home. Their service also kept food and beverage businesses alive when dine-in was not allowed.

Regardless of rain or shine, they continue to work ,and often race to deliver food to us bicycle, motorbikes or even mobility aid because most deliveries happens during those few meal hours.  Some food delivery heroes continue this race to deliver despite their mobility challenge in order to earn a living for survival.

After every rain, a rainbow may appear. After every night,¬† a new sunrise and a new hope for the day. Thank you to all the food delivery heroes for your dedication. Stay safe and strong. Let's be more patient if your food delivery took longer. 

 Hope that this pandemic will be over soon and we get back to the good old norm.

Photo 1 - Racing to deliver on bicycle in the hot sun

Photo 2 - Racing to deliver on bicycle in heavy rain

Photo 3 - Racing to deliver on motorcycle

Photo 4 - Racing to deliver on mobility aid in front of vibrant rainbow decoration

Photo 5 - Food delivery hero seen getting ready to start their day during sunrise at Changi beach

¬¶ Photography is like a box of chocolates ¬¶ 

Forrest Gump: My momma always said, ‚ÄúLife was like a box of chocolates. You never know what you're gonna get.‚Äù... so is photographing NDP rehearsals... ü§™. 

After shooting rehearsal after rehearsal, i wanted to "make an image", (a different view/composition).
And after pre-visualizing, selecting the position n camera settings, and going through the motion, did not expect another photographer decided to shift his position to "lord" over n above my position, laterally "walks into my frame" ..üòÇ
So would like to paraphrase ‚Äúphotography is like a box of chocolates, is full of surprises; you never know what will happen next, and that's the joy of photography.. ü§£ü§£ü§£

Saying a prayer for peace, luck and wealth at the temple has been a culture and ritual for many a Chinese during the Chinese New Year.  The  Kwan Im Thong Hood Cho Temple in Waterloo St is one popular temple where thousands of devotees flock to to offer prayers at the stroke of midnight on the first day of CNY.  Many youths today have also practised these intangible heritage of religious culture passed down for generations.

While NDP 2020 is touted to be different from the past years, many including myself believed the NDPs of yesteryear at the Grand Old Dame of Kallang National Stadium were the ones to beat.  With 60000 spectators + thousands of participants and organisers in and around the stadium, the atmosphere could only be bettered by the Kallang Roar of the Malaysia Cup heydays. 
The Stadium literally rocked whenever Fandi and company scored a goal.  This panoramic view was taken during the NDP 2003.  The last NDP was held there in 2006 before it bid sayonara in 2007.  Will NDP ever return to the Grand Dame ?  After the 2016 experience, your guess is as good as mine.

Emotions stirred up as the bus pass through the streets of Chinatown, some found themselves separated from their families in Singapore with no idea when they could return, after the country closed its borders. 

Most foreign workers are not as lucky as many whom are still able to spend quality time with their loved ones, I sincerely hope they will be able to reunion back with their love ones soon.

The Frontline Story.
To many of us, COVID19 Pandemic is merely a period of inconvience, restriction and disruption. But for the medical frontliners, the coronavirus pandemic is a time of anxiety, stress, worry, concern and separation.  While medical professionals have not shun their responsibility and stoically face the challenge head-on, they have to contend with the inconvience of donning the Personal Protective Equipment day in and day out as they go about their duty testing, swapping and treating people infected by the virus.  However uncomfortable the PPE is, they understand the need to protect not only themselves, but also the patients, fellow medical colleagues and all frontline staff. According to staff who have experience with PPE, it takes time to put on the PPE securely. Because of this, many staff stay on their shift work for as long as they can, putting off meal and toilet breaks wherever possible to avoid the hassle of removing and putting on the PPE again. This has taken a toll on their health, not to mention the stress of their jobs. Because of the potential exposure to the virus, many of the doctors and nurses who are directly involved with Covid patients voluntarily stay away from the family members to protect them.  Unable to be with and see their families have also put them under more emotional stress.  Unless we step into their shoes, we will never know what they went through in their gruelling daily schedule
Kudos to all medical personnel as they fought to keep Singapore safe. Your collective effort will one day see Singapore COVID-free. 
Together A Stronger Singapore üá∏üá¨

The Hindu festival of Thaipusam is celebrated on the full moon day in the Tamil month of Thai. Thaipusam is a thanksgiving festival where devotees celebrate the fulfilment of their vows. A compilation of the beautiful house of Tan Teng Niah; 
Built in 1900, the former house of Tan Teng Niah is the last surviving Chinese villa in Little India. Tan Teng Niah was a¬†towkay¬†(Chinese businessman of good standing) Many believe that Tan built the house for his wife and that the inscription referred to her.¬†The design of the house were beautifully crafted including the main door inscription made just for his wife. Note of the blossom flowers on the windows. The former house of Tan Teng Niah has eight rooms.

To the Chinese, the house design was auspiciously designed. Each doorway was beautifully decorated with carvings including the twirling wooden stairway of the golden dragons which impressed me most. The carvings were so detailed, precise and elegantly designed. Kudos to the 1900s skillful carpenters. 

The house was restored and conserved in the 1980s for commercial use, and the restoration project was awarded the Singapore Institute of Architects Honourable Mention in 1991. It is partially rented out Mr Chandran who had been there for more than 10years. He is a retired police officer whom set up this flower bussiness. I  was fortunate to have him sharing of his experiences and allowing me to take the beautiful interior of the villa.

The increase in demand for energy worldwide has put a strain on the limited non-renewable energy sources like coal and crude oil.  It is therefore crucial to develop alternative renewable energy sources like solar and wind energy.  Singapore has embarked on tapping solar energy as an alternative energy souces by implementing solar panels atop HDB blocks and reservoirs.  While the energy generated by these panels are not sufficient to cater to our needs at the moment, the advancement in solar technology one day would.

This is one of the nurses I know. Covid-19 has changed the way medicine is practiced completely. There were a lot of fear and uncertainties at the beginning.  Changes in workflow occurred almost daily as the medical community struggled to keep up with the latest findings and developments about the virus. 

One of the changes that impacted frontline workers was the need to gear up in personal protective equipment. The n95 mask was suffocating and left imprints or even abrasions on the nose bridge and cheeks. The face shield kept fogging up and it was challenging to see through the fog and reflections. The gown was crumblesome and hot. The gloves removed that personal touch with the patients.

Yet, at the end of the day, she smiled brightly, happy to play her part towards patient care. I am so inspired by her and other frontline workers who are fighting the COVID-19 battle bravely!

9 August 2020 is Singapore's 55th National Day, and it also marks the day when I finish my National Service (NS) to the nation. Even though I didn't have a choice in serving, where I would serve, and what I would be doing, it has been a remarkable journey of seeing God's provision for my family and I. In my very short time of being on the ground I've seen suicides, wrestled drunks, and arrested criminals, among a host of other things. I'm thankful for the individuals who've been put in my path to mentor and guide me, not just in the technical aspects of my job, but in the soft skills as well- how to be sympathetic yet neutral, calm yet firm, swift yet alert, proactive yet working as a team. There is no other place where acquiring these skills is as crucial and relevant as the Singapore Police Force. NS can be a shit-show and a waste of time. Or it can be a training ground for growth and personal development. The single determining factor is your MINDSET towards it.

Excited for the future of our garden city üåÉüå≥

üì∑: @yean_to_travel ‚Ä¢ Modern versus traditional public housing in Singapore. 

The Pinnacle at Duxton shows how much public housing in Singapore has evolved over the past 60 years. It is built on the site of Singapore's oldest Housing Development Board's blocks. Being the world's tallest public housing, it soars above the neighbourhood at 50 storeys in height. It also features the world's longest sky gardens! This showcases innovation and greenery in designing public housing in land-scarce Singapore, making her a garden city.

Instead of focusing on the things that don't matter, get obsessed with who you're becoming, where you're going and all of the amazing things you're going to accomplish!

More than ever, this year in which everything has been on pause, has been the best time to do everything you always wanted to do! Your personal projects, your side-hustles, etc!

To think that there is only 3 months left to this year is crazy, but don‚Äôt let that time pass by, use it wisely and create!

It has been such a year, not much travel, but on a positive side, I got to see so much more of what Singapore has to offer, to create great friendships and have many wonderful projects involving talented people.

Hope that you got the chance to optimize this weird 2020 as well and celebrate little wins!

The Road to Better Lives

Low skilled foreign workers in our country -- integral to many aspects of our lives today; large in numbers and isolated -- and their poor living conditions went largely unnoticed before COVID-19. Despite contributing to the many undesirable industries of Singapore, they aren't always appreciated and recognised. The road to better lives -- theirs and ours -- is ahead and we all have a part to play.

Vanishing Points.
Yet Con Chicken Rice. Purvis Street, Singapore. April 2014.
.

Dug up an old photograph of this classic restaurant taken in 2014. Incidentally, I also discovered that Royston Tan ( @filmr )  had recently featured a short film about Yet Con. I am always inspired by the stories he tells about nostalgic places, so do check it out on @rewindsingapore 
.
 
Places like Yet Con Restaurant are one of those special landmarks and favorable destinations for families in Singapore since the early 50s, which are either gone or disappearing.
.

Things are changing around us so fast that sometimes the only thing you have is a photograph to remember a space or a person. As Royston shared it best, "spaces become places when we give meaning to them. They represent memories that we treasure, moments that we want to re-live, and times that we don‚Äôt want to forget. They represent us.‚Äù 
.
.

post_caption:
PARKROYAL on Pickering is an iconic green structure, with a hotel-in-a-garden design, reflecting Singapore as a garden-city.

With 15,000 square metres of sky-gardens, pools, waterfalls, planter terraces and cascading vertical greenery, it's lush foliage constitutes more than 200% of the total land area!

It has won several awards including BCA Green Mark Platinum and Solar Pioneer Award. 

Am really glad to see the positive changes in Singapore where more developments includes features for sustainability.

Before the appearance of convenience stores like 7-11, we had old Mama (in Tamil, mama means uncle) shops around every neighbourhood. These small shops were mostly started by early Indian immigrants.
. 

Cigarettes, sweets, batteries, magazine, newspapers and comic books, are some of the popular items you can find at a typical mama shop.
.

This was one of the last remaining mama shop situated along a 'five foot way' in Arab Street. #fujifilm #sgmemory

The increase in demand for energy worldwide has put a strain on the limited non-renewable energy sources like coal and crude oil.  It is therefore crucial to develop alternative renewable energy sources like solar and wind energy.  Singapore has embarked on tapping solar energy as an alternative energy souces by implementing solar panels atop HDB blocks and reservoirs.  While the energy generated by these panels are not sufficient to cater to our needs at the moment, the advancement in solar technology one day would.

To many us, COVID19 Pandemic is merely a period of inconvience, restriction and disruption. But for the medical frontliners, the coronavirus pandemic is a time of anxiety, stress, worry, concern and separation. While every medical professional has not shun their responsibility and stoically face the challenge head-on, they have to contend with the inconvience of donning the Personal Protective Equipment day in day out as they go about their duty testing and treating people infected by the virus. However uncomfortable the PPE is, they understand the need to protect not only themselves, but also the patients, fellow medical colleagues and all frontline staff. Kudos to all medical personnel as they fought to keep Singapore safe. Your collective effort will one day see Singapore COVID-free.  Thank you üá∏üá¨

If you a fan of traditional kopitiam that has not only traditionally brewed authentic coffee aroma but also an old uncle complete in his iconic blue-strip pyjamas, then this time-stood-still coffee shop is for you.  Toasted bread are done over charcoal fire and coffee are done pouring in and out of the brownish-stained coffee bag.  There is even a good olden day timber counter that is no longer used by a cashier, but are stack with traditional biscuits and cookies kept in containers that appear to be used since day one.  If Singapore is serious about preserving its food culture, then this shop has to be gazetted for its intangible cultural heritage that dated back to the 60s and 70s

"All colours üåà on a tree!" 

Eucalyptus deglupta is a species of tall tree, commonly known as the rainbow eucalyptus, Mindanao gum, or rainbow gum that is native to the Philippines, Indonesia, and Papua New Guinea.
The rainbow effect is created as the bark peels off throughout each season, revealing the fresh, bright-green bark below.¬†As each layer of bark matures, it turns shades of blue, purple, orange, and red.

If you want to know exactly how the trees' bark becomes rainbow-hued, or to witness this beautiful rainbow eucalyptus trees, you are in luck. 

Here in Singapore, the one and only! 
The heritage Mindanao Gum Tree in Katong Park, Singapore.

Provision shop in a home. 80-year-old Mr Ang is the key figure at Tee Seng Store and has been working here since 1955. Waking up at 5am everyday to practise¬†qigong¬†before opening his shop at 8am as he wants to stay get healthy so that he can continue to work here with his beloved wife.

He knows his regular what they want even before they asked. One of his customer shared the store has the biggest and fresh eggs.
An empty Milkmaid tin that was used to store cash in the past. Mr Ang now uses a scanner cash register.

What impressed me most was Mr Ang had learnt many languages  like Thai, Java, Tagalog, Malay, Tamil and Sinhala. He shared knowing these languages helps give that personal touch to the customers. Of course there's one language he wished to pick up and thats Jap. 

I am fortunate that Mr Ang allows me to take a shot of him and chat with his childhood days and all his experience since young till now and of course this kampung¬†spirit and experience is something supermarket chains can never give you...

Cutest murals in our backyard @chinatownsingapore

PARKROYAL Collection on Pickering is literally a garden oasis in downtown Singapore.  The building's "hotel-in-a-garden" concept has been lauded for its unique architecture and eco-friendly design.  It is a tropical wonderland with greenery flourishes throughout the entire 15000 sqm of elevated terraced gardens.  From solar powered systems to rain harvesting to save water, the building is built with sustainability in mind.  Among the prestigious awards and accolades it has garnered is the Singapore Green Hotel Award 2016-2018.

Many youths today have also practised these intangible heritage of religious culture passed down for generations.

Nine Emperor Gods Festival 2020
Leong Nam Temple ÈæçÂçóÊÆø‰πùÁöáÂ§ß‰∫åÂ∏ùÁà∑ÂçÉÁßã
@ East Coast Park

The Nine Emperor Gods Festival is generally held from the last day of the eighth lunar month to the ninth day of the ninth lunar month among Chinese communities in Southeast Asia. 
Devotees believe that the Nine Emperor Gods bestow wealth and longevity on their worshippers. Rituals held during the festival differ among temples in different countries.
It begins with the welcoming procession of the gods from the sea into the temple where they are to be worshipped for nine days, and ends when the gods are sent off procession also via the sea on the ninth day. 

This year the festival has scaled down considerably due to the Covid pandemic. Devotees, however, are still welcome to pray to the dieties but have to observe the social distancing measures in the temples.

[LAST CALL]

#MadAboutSingapore2020c is a call for pictures taken from 23rd January 2020 - that's when the first case in Singapore was confirmed. ‚ÄúC‚Äù is an indication of the challenging time of COVID-19 - it is not life as usual. We now recognise that we are living through a major global crisis, which will be remembered for generations to come. As visual storytellers, it is our responsibility to use our passions to document this period as best as we can, that future generations might see and learn ‚Äì and be inspired by the passion and courage of people who lived through this time.

We are requesting you to tag any pictures related to this with #MadAboutSingapore2020c - this can be pictures that show the impacts, the changes around SG because of COVID-19, and perhaps encouraging images of how we strive and make it possible to cope with this hard time, and support each other in moving forward. There is no image, no encounter too small or unimportant ‚Äì let‚Äôs build a visual history not just of the big events, but our day-to-day lives as well.

Together with us, the team behind @Singapore is also appreciative of your creative effort to document this. We will browse this hashtag, and once in a while we might select some pictures to be featured, either on @instasg or @Singapore. Beside the features, we also have a few very nice portable LED lights given to us as gifts, from a long-term supportive partner that decided to stay low profile for now :) We will select one of the best pictures at the end of this month, and we will pass the LED light as a gift.

For the last round, our judging panel will start browsing the hashtag after Sept 20th, and we hope to have the winner within a week.

We look forward to your shots on #MadAboutSingapore2020c! Please stay safe, always keep in mind the safe distance and personal hygiene. Avoid crowded place and do not go out unnecessarily. Together we shall overcome!

#ThisIsSG #MadAboutSingapore #SGunited #SingaporeTogether #CommunitySpirit

To many us, COVID19 Pandemic is merely a period of inconvience, restriction and disruption. But for the medical frontliners, the coronavirus pandemic is a time of anxiety, stress, worry, concern and separation. While every medical professional has not shun their responsibility and stoically face the challenge head-on, they have to contend with the inconvience of donning the Personal Protective Equipment day in day out as they go about their duty testing and treating people infected by the virus. However uncomfortable the PPE is, they understand the need to protect not only themselves, but also the patients, fellow medical colleagues and all frontline staff. Kudos to all medical personnel as they fought to keep Singapore safe. Your collective effort will one day see Singapore COVID-free. Thank you üá∏üá¨

One of my favourite green spaces in Singapore is Gardens by the Bay, Singapore. You can see plants and trees flourishing around this lake. 

Did you know that water run-off from within the Gardens is captured by the lake system and cleansed by aquatic plants before being discharged into the Marina reservoir? Water from the lake system is also used in the built-in irrigation system for the Gardens. Aquatic plants play a major role in the functioning of the ecosystem and clean water is vital for sustaining biodiversity. 

Let's all do our part for sustainability in Singapore!

The good old days at Tee Seng Store. Putting everything together, hope u like it...

Provision shop in a home. 80-year-old Mr Ang is the key figure at Tee Seng Store and has been working here since 1955. Waking up at 5am everyday to practise¬†qigong¬†before opening his shop at 8am as he wants to stay get healthy so that he can continue to work here with his beloved wife.

He knows his regular what they want even before they asked. One of his customer shared the store has the biggest and fresh eggs.
An empty Milkmaid tin that was used to store cash in the past. Mr Ang now uses a scanner cash register.

What impressed me most was Mr Ang had learnt many languages  like Thai, Java, Tagalog, Malay, Tamil and Sinhala. He shared knowing these languages helps give that personal touch to the customers. Of course there's one language he wished to pick up and thats Jap. 

I am fortunate that Mr Ang allows me to take a shot of him and chat with his childhood days and all his experience since young till now and of course this kampung¬†spirit and experience is something supermarket chains can never give you...

My #mpnd2020 1 minute video is up... for greetings and wishes.
I sang part of the community song that i wrote for my neighbourhood as Marley the caring dolphin üê¨ is busily caring for people in the community during Covid19 situation. Instead of way, Marley wants to show the care...

Yes, this year is the year of many changes as we had to don on masks when we go out except during exercise. Covid19 situation has indeed change our lifestyle and we have to celebrate differently from the usual norm.

We should learn more to be like Marley the dolphin üê¨ to care for the community and have the dolphinüê¨ spirit in us as dolphins do stay positive regardless of the situation. We should learn to be more like dolphins for its willpower and determination to overcome adversities. Even if we feel tired... regardless of frontliner or not...

Soon mobile phone become the indispensable item of the day till an Apple grows in Marina Bay Singapore today.  How have your lives change with the mobile device ?

Today is the 15th day of the 8 month in the Chinese calendar. It is the day set aside for family reunions, but also the time when the moon is at its most bright.  The Mid Autumn Festival or Moon Festival will have people gather to sample autumn harvests. In our case, most people here enjoy mooncakes, consisting of many tasty flavors üòã Usually it is a crazy travelling moment all across Asia but I guess this year is quite a special year eh?!

Happy Mid Autumn Festival to all our friends out there. What is the best tasting mooncake you have had? Have you had one before?

Uncle Shi, aka Uncle in Pajamas, is keeping the butter coffee and other Singapore traditions alive despite the challenging time. 83-year old uncle sat in a class for certification when the shop had to close for few weeks during the circuit breaker implementation. Most of us might choose to complain about inconvenience, lost of business opportunities and demand for government helps - while this uncle chose to be out of his comfort zone in order to continue reminding us of Singapore values when we start picking up the new normal.

Safe entry barcode is there, remember to scan when you get there for a chat with old friend over kopi and kaya toast, or even if you are going to be there for few minutes only to tabao your daily dose of kopi.

Nine Emperor Gods Festival 2020
Leong Nam Temple ÈæçÂçóÊÆø‰πùÁöáÂ§ß‰∫åÂ∏ùÁà∑ÂçÉÁßã
@ East Coast Park

The Nine Emperor Gods Festival is generally held from the last day of the eighth lunar month to the ninth day of the ninth lunar month among Chinese communities in Southeast Asia. 
Devotees believe that the Nine Emperor Gods bestow wealth and longevity on their worshippers. Rituals held during the festival differ among temples in different countries.
It begins with the welcoming procession of the gods from the sea into the temple where they are to be worshipped for nine days, and ends when the gods are sent off procession also via the sea on the ninth day. 

This year the festival has scaled down considerably due to the Covid pandemic. Devotees, however, are still welcome to pray to the dieties but have to observe the social distancing measures in the temples.

¬¶ 55th National Day & 55,000+ Covid-19 infections ¬¶ 
. 
The first case of the COVID-19 in Singapore was confirmed on 23 January 2020. Early cases were primarily imported until local transmission began to develop in February and March. By late-March and April, COVID-19 clusters were detected at multiple dormitories for foreign workers, which soon contributed to an overwhelming proportion of new cases in the country. 

While celebrating our 55th year of nation building on 9 August, that another milestone has been crossed. Fortunately, the projection that infection cases shall be tapering off, also that is if everyone complies with the measures for local community cases. 
Due to earlier strict "circuit breaker" (shelter in home) measures, transient nature and time of the day's events, posted here will be some of the images that were recorded for posterity.

ÈæçÂçóÊÆø‰πùÁöáÂ§ß‰∫åÂ∏ùÁà∑ÂçÉÁßã

The Nine Emperor Gods Festival is generally held from the last day of the eighth lunar month to the ninth day of the ninth lunar month among Chinese communities in Southeast Asia.

Devotees believe that the Nine Emperor Gods bestow wealth and longevity on their worshippers. Rituals held during the festival differ among temples in different countries.
It begins with the welcoming procession of the gods from the sea into the temple where they are to be worshipped for nine days, and ends when the gods are sent off procession also via the sea on the ninth day. 

This year the festival has scaled down considerably due to the Covid pandemic. Devotees, however, are still welcome to pray to the dieties but have to observe the social distancing measures in the temples.

Jewel Changi Airport reflects the sustainability efforts of Singapore and her reputation as a garden city. 

Rain water is harvested and then recirculated to the fountain of the HSBC rain vortex, the highest indoor waterfall. It's vapour is used to ventilate and cool the interior.

Five floors of gardens, featuring over 900 trees and 60,000 shrubs from all around the world, surround the Rain Vortex, functioning as a green lung. 

It was deservingly awarded a sustainability certificate, the Green Mark Gold Award.

Am glad to see positive changes towards greater emphasis in sustainability in Singapore.

During the pandemic, one of the hardest groups of people who got affected was our construction workers who were staying in the dormitories. Construction works came to almost a total halt.

9 August 2020.
 Singapore's 55th birthday.

Missing the usual NDP. Makes you realise how significant it is.

Working today is something I have not done so for awhile.

Reminds me of NDP 2006, where I was the last marching contingent to ever march out of the old Kallang Stadium. The waving flags, the kallang wave, and different voices singing as one were unforgettable scenes.

Hope we will get back together again in 9 August 2021.

TWG Tea

If you've ever traveled through Singapore Changi Airport, you may have stumbled upon this shop. It's eye catching interior decoration and design showcases around 800 of their tea collection.

TWG Tea, the finest luxury tea brand in the world, was established in Singapore and celebrates the year 1837 when the island became a trading post for teas, spices and fine epicurean products.

Chinatown Singapore Mid-Autumn Festival Lightup 2020.
Rain or shine, covid or not, the Mid-Autumn Festival @chinatown_festivals is on.  Kudos to the organisers for lighting up Chinatown to bring some festive cheers to the sombre mood brought about by the pandemic.  Although the hustle and bustle of night markets is missing, lesser crowd allows people to enjoy the colourful lanterns lightup more.

Singapore is known as a garden city and I am always grateful for the green spaces you can find in this bustling city. Gardens by the Bay has lush greenery and lakes systems that filters the rain water before draining into the Marina Reservoir. 

The Marina Barrage is a dam built across the Marina channel, forming the Marina Reservoir,  Singapore's largest catchment area. 

They were both designed and constructed with conservation and sustainability in mind. Am glad to see so many positive changes towards greater emphasis in sustainability in Singapore. Do check out the Sustainable Singapore Gallery if you are at the barrage!

Karma is an action, not a result. The future is not set in stone as you can change the course of your life at this very moment by changing your intentional acts and self-destructive patterns.

Karma is energy and it‚Äôs our intentional thoughts and actions. The energy we generate now and in the future will affect us. It has nothing to do with reward or punishment. 

For us, our karma is treating life as big collaboration. Individually, we are one drop. 
Together, we are an ocean.
Daily, in your own little ways, the best we can all do is stay positive, support each other and put a smile on the face of people around. 

Kindness, Positivity, Support, Collaboration always win.
Anger, Negativity, Resentment, Jealousy ... well we don't care about the outcome as they are ignored and dismissed.

Stay positive! Keep communucating with your loved ones and we will go through this 2020 year all fine üôèüèº

"The Uncle in Pajamas", that's how we call him. Uncle Shi has been running Heap Seng Leong since 1974, but it's not really just about selling coffee.

Uncle Shi made a committed decision to keep the coffee and the cafe true to Singapore culture, something that he grew up with after arriving in Singapore with his father when he was 12. He chose to keep the jars of biscuits there too although it might not sell well, because that‚Äôs how his father started when they arrived, making biscuits to sustain the family. He keeps the old Singapore atmosphere alive with his business, and his son is also fully prepared to continue this family tradition for as long as they can.

Keeping such cultural value is not easy in the age of Starbucks and dalgona coffee. But uncle Shi is a seasoned fighter that has overcome multiple periods of economy crisis and business challenges. If SARS was not enough, just few months ago they had to close the business for few weeks while the 83-year old uncle attended a class to get the safe business certification, so that he could still deliver the kopi for those who need to be reminded of themselves as Singaporeans. He simply had to keep the tradition going on in the toughest time of the generation. 

For his resilience in keeping the Singapore values alive, I hope DBS bank can support him.

@dbsbank if you want the #portraitsofpurpose, this is it.

Disclaimer: I had a little chat with Uncle Shi and his son, he agreed to pose and they are aware that this picture will be submitted for photography contest.

Embrace change - Learning to appreciate, observe and imagine more

2020 is a year of change and uncertainty. I start to appreciate and observe small little things more. In particular, I tend to be more observant of light especially during those rare occassions that I can go out to buy essential items during pandemic period. I did not go out specially to take photo. This was taken during one of my visit to buy essential. I had a camera with me and I saw the amazing light in a unique scene. When a subject came by, I snapped and got the shot. Embracing the change - learning to appreciate, observe and imagine more instead of snapping mindlessly more - does helped in getting better shots.

‚ÄúA two-stage plan, which will transform Singapore into a beautiful garden city with flowers and trees, without waste and as neat and orderly as possible‚Äù said the late PM Lee Kuan Yew in The Straits Times on 12 May 1967. At the end of 1970, more than 55,000 new trees had been planted. The number then increased from approximately 158,600 in 1974 to 1.4 million in June 2014. Currently at Gardens By The Bay alone there are more than 150,000.

Singapore‚Äôs Garden City project also gave birth to the Parks and Trees Act in 1975, required government and private agencies to reserve spaces for trees and vegetation. Green building has been mandatory since 2008 in Singapore. It is normal to find plants on the top and the sides of buildings (like cascading gardens) and also inside the buildings.

It‚Äôs a great vision by the founding fathers, great men who could foresee our need decades ahead even before UN Sustainable Development Goals were defined. It‚Äôs also good to see how the government keeps the commitment to build an environmental sustainable country. Peace, prosperity and progress... indeed.

Nine Emperor Gods Festival 2020
@ Leong Nam Temple 
ÈæçÂçóÊÆø‰πùÁöáÂ§ß‰∫åÂ∏ùÁà∑Âú£ËØû 
Rain or shine...devotees come in drove to offer prayers to the Nine Emperor Gods.
The Nine Emperor Gods Festival is generally held from the last day of the eighth lunar month to the ninth day of the ninth lunar month among Chinese communities in Southeast Asia. 
Devotees believe that the Nine Emperor Gods bestow wealth and longevity on their worshippers. Rituals held during the festival differ among temples in different countries.
It begins with the welcoming procession of the gods from the sea into the temple where they are to be worshipped for nine days, and ends when the gods are sent off procession also via the sea on the ninth day. Today, the younger generations have taken an interest in the festival, with many youths taking part in the processions. Involving the younger generations allows us to continue this intangible cultural heritage for many generations to come.

Have you ever wondered what changes occurred on the spot you are standing at?

Don't forget that you can also have a mental vacation, because those are just as important as the physical ones!

Some things can drain your energy and you definitely need to unplug!
The next time you feel anxious, ask yourself this: Does this deserve my energy? If it is a no, take a deep breath, disconnect, and come back IN FORCE!

And anyways, we can't really go on a physical vacation, so we went to Sentosa Island, formerly used as a British military base and then a Japanese prisoner-of-war camp in Singapore. Home of many theme parks, resorts, fun attractions and beach clubs, a stop here is a must whether you are a visitor or a local! #SingapoRediscovers

One of my favourite nature spots in Singapore is the Jurong Lake Gardens. The 90-hectare gardens has nature trails and attractions around the lake, with grasslands, swamp forests and wetlands. It also has many features for sustainability such as swales and bioretention basins to cleanse the water runoff from the rain. The rain water collected is harvested to water the plants and also circulated through biotopes and phytoremediation ponds, which clean the water over time.¬†

Let's all do our part for sustainability in Singapore!

The Blind Side. 
Singapore. December 2019.
.

Writing is something I don‚Äôt do very often for the reason I keep telling myself that I am not a good writer. As I ponder this, my mind just starts wrestling with that conflict. The irony is unless you write more, you‚Äôre never going to be better at writing anything. Holding that same thought about taking photographs, unless I constantly make an effort to see things, people, or places through a viewfinder, and using my camera, I am never going to be better at crafting images.
.

LOL! Why so deep Mike? You might ask. I was rather intrigued by an insightful conversation I had this morning with a friend. It‚Äôs interesting how powerful Instagram can be as a channel for providing exposure to what we want the world to see, but at the same time, as with any social platform (if we allow that to ‚Äòdictate‚Äô our desires), we could easily be blindsided into letting it shape our emotions and distort our idea of what‚Äôs good and what‚Äôs perfectly meaningful.
.

Just so you know, I do naturally enjoy the comments and likes on my posts. However, I think I have gotten passed that threshold about whether the value system of my posts is measured by the number of likes. What‚Äôs keeping me more passionate is knowing whether I can connect with the images I photograph. Am I sharpening my craft and getting better at what I do? Am I bold enough to try different things creatively even despite what I might consider it‚Äôs not my forte? Am I copying instead of innovating?
.

Perhaps this might be a longer than usual chatter‚Ä¶ but I felt this image today gives a sort of semiotic element to my thoughts about the topic. If you‚Äôre reading through this, thank you for reading, and hello from sunny Singapore. üòäüëãüèªüá∏üá¨
.
.

Before what is now the National Gallery, it was two buildings; the Supreme Court and the Post Office. There was a space in between these buildings, presumably a street of sorts. After the renovation, it is now covered and turned two separate historical buildings into one incredible architecture. This proves that with some imagination and enough effort, two complete different entities can be joined to become one beautiful creation.

[Montage 2020] My Story

Little India Photo Series.

I was born, grew up and currently living near Little India. This place, is now like a touristy and instagrammable place, because Little India, is simply colourful and vibrant, with lots of culture. This is the reason why it has inspired me, to become a street photographer, regularly documenting the sights and sounds, of Little India. 

I have fond memories of the current Tekka Market but very vague memory of the old Tekka market, where it was demolished in 1982 and move across the street to the current location. I am glad they put up the poster of the old market, which brings back great memories

This the Covid year and the carton boxes you see here, forms a barrier, to restrict and control crowd, going into the market

First 3 photos taken by Nikon camera, the rest taken by mobile

The Lone Tree, our current #instagramtree that you would see in many wedding pictures nowadays. According to NParks; it is a sculpture made from recycled iron reinforcement bars salvaged from the old park‚Äôs path, an inspired way of reusing materials and an ode to the industrial origins of Jurong.

Jurong Lake Gardens, where you can find this tree, is a proof of how much the government of Singapore puts as effort to reach the UN Sustainability Goals, especially goal #11 - sustainable cities and communities. Sustainability has always been the main consideration in urban planning and development, just look around Singapore and no one can deny this. I guess it‚Äôs back to the people now, how serious are we in creating a sustainable tomorrow for our children?

WALL-E is one of my all time favorites movies, and there are few similar movies that have done a great job in warning us. Will our children be able to climb a real tree, or would they look at the monument like this one and learn about the trees from a history book?

#MadAboutSingapore2020c is a call for pictures taken from 23rd January 2020 - that's when the first case in Singapore was confirmed. ‚ÄúC‚Äù is an indication of the challenging time of COVID-19 - it is not life as usual. We now recognise that we are living through a major global crisis, which will be remembered for generations to come. As visual storytellers, it is our responsibility to use our passions to document this period as best as we can, that future generations might see and learn ‚Äì and be inspired by the passion and courage of people who lived through this time.

We are requesting you to tag any pictures related to this with #MadAboutSingapore2020c - this can be pictures that show the impacts, the changes around SG because of COVID-19, and perhaps encouraging images of how we strive and make it possible to cope with this hard time, and support each other in moving forward. There is no image, no encounter too small or unimportant ‚Äì let‚Äôs build a visual history not just of the big events, but our day-to-day lives as well.

Together with us, the team behind @Singapore is also appreciative of your creative effort to document this. We will browse this hashtag, and once in a while we might select some pictures to be featured, either on @instasg or @Singapore. "RAWR!!!"

That's the roar of the father moments before he lunged forward to hug his preschooler child. The kid appears to be startled, but opened his arms anyway to receive the embrace of his loving father.

This picture was taken at the #digitallightcanvas at the #marinabaysands. I happened to be chilling at Rasapura Masters (Koufu), and the canvas was just opened to allow entry for the excited kids and their parents/guardians. Aside from the reminder to wear a mask and having their temperature taken, every person who enters is also given a pair of disposable rubber gloves, likely to minimize the chance of catching the coronavirus. They even have little gloves for the children.

It's nice to see people having fun, while taking precautionary measures seriously.

Construction Workforce

Considered as the backbone of Singapore's infrastructure development, most of them are comprised of foreign workers who work tirelessly day and night in the construction industry.

In Singapore, you will usually see them doing maintenance works along the road, in the railway transit or in renovation areas wearing full PPE'S while still maintaining their smile and greeting you nicely even in the scorching heat.

To me, they are one of the unsung heroes that needs to be credited and acknowledged for their hardwork and contribution to Singapore considering that their sector is hard stricken by Covid-19. Hands down to them.

Nine Emperor Gods Festival 2020
Leong Nam Temple ÈæçÂçóÊÆø‰πùÁöáÂ§ß‰∫åÂ∏ùÁà∑ÂçÉÁßã
@ East Coast Park

The Nine Emperor Gods Festival is generally held from the last day of the eighth lunar month to the ninth day of the ninth lunar month among Chinese communities in Southeast Asia. 
Devotees believe that the Nine Emperor Gods bestow wealth and longevity on their worshippers. Rituals held during the festival differ among temples in different countries.
It begins with the welcoming procession of the gods from the sea into the temple where they are to be worshipped for nine days, and ends when the gods are sent off procession also via the sea on the ninth day. 

This year the festival has scaled down considerably due to the Covid pandemic. Devotees, however, are still welcome to pray to the dieties but have to observe the social distancing measures in the temples.

Congrats to @hoodzie_ - winner of the July #madaboutsingapore2020c. Please contact us for more details on ow to claim the portable LCD light, a monthly prize for this.

Thanks to everyone who has been participating too, please continue to tag your picture as we have one last prize and we will close this on Sept 15th.

#MadAboutSingapore2020c is a call for pictures taken from 23rd January 2020 - that's when the first case in Singapore was confirmed. ‚ÄúC‚Äù is an indication of the challenging time of COVID-19 - it is not life as usual. We now recognise that we are living through a major global crisis, which will be remembered for generations to come. As visual storytellers, it is our responsibility to use our passions to document this period as best as we can, that future generations might see and learn ‚Äì and be inspired by the passion and courage of people who lived through this time.

We are requesting you to tag any pictures related to this with #MadAboutSingapore2020c - this can be pictures that show the impacts, the changes around SG because of COVID-19, and perhaps encouraging images of how we strive and make it possible to cope with this hard time, and support each other in moving forward. There is no image, no encounter too small or unimportant ‚Äì let‚Äôs build a visual history not just of the big events, but our day-to-day lives as well.

Together with us, the team behind @Singapore is also appreciative of your creative effort to document this. We will browse this hashtag, and once in a while we might select some pictures to be featured, either on @instasg or @Singapore. Beside the features, we also have a few very nice portable LED lights given to us as gifts, from a long-term supportive partner that decided to stay low profile for now.

Our panel has decided to extend this last round a bit longer, please continue to post and tag until Sept 15th, and we will start looking at your pictures shortly after that.

All the best, and please stay safe - don‚Äôt purposely go out to shoot and please avoid crowd for now. Keep your hands clean at all times and wear mask, together we shall overcome!

Work from home - Reflection of change

Most work in offices as the norm. Covid-19 pandemic brought upon the change where working from home became the norm. It was particularly challenging for working parents, like my family, during the circuit breaker period where we worked from home with kiddy everyday. It is not easy juggling teleconferences and kiddy care. As I reflect, we embraced the change and survived. Nothing is impossible. Just need reason to be the change. In this case, for the safety of our family and others.

Mr and Mrs Sow sell vegetarian chicken rice at Teck Ghee hawker. I got a chance to talked to them and asked why they started to sell such a nice vegetarian chicken rice. Mrs Sow shared me because of her devotedness of Buddhist as Mr Sow used to sell real chicken rice before. Mr Sow was willing to converted from real chicken rice to vegetarian chicken rice since 7years ago. It was truly inspiring and touching story. I always appreciate hawker cultures and their story behind.

>
This year, the flying routes ‚ÄúRoar of Unity‚Äù include special appearances at Sengkang General Hospital and the rest of seven hospitals. 
>
This is to pay tribute to our frontline fighters and essential workers for their spirit and resilience as they battle against COVID-19 pandemic.
>
We, the people of Singapore, are clapping and cheering for our healthcare workers. Truly a heartwarming moment.

Singapore is known as a Garden City and Gardens by the Bay truly embodies this. Flourishing plants and flowers line both sides of Marina Reservoir, the largest catchment in Singapore.

The conservatories and lake systems have incorporated many features for energy conservation and sustainability. For example, the rain water collected in the lakes are used for irrigation and solar panels on the supertrees offset the energy required for the light show. 

Am encouraged to see so much efforts put into conservation and sustainability in Singapore. These green spaces also provide locals with a place to relax, unwind and immerse in nature.

During the circuit breaker in April I entered my 9th month of pregnancy. The city situation didn‚Äôt deter from doing our little maternity photo shoot in-house with my 6 year old daughter and my mate took the shots indoor to capture our moments for memories of lifetime..

We were optimistic and felt totally safe bringing our second child in the red dot üî¥ country üá∏üá¨ 

Our spirits were high as you can see in the pic and we were geared to take on the challenges of the situation. We complied and never fretted over being home locked for our own good. Being home was the way and the baby arrival was a time to celebrate and we did just that!

I gave birth to a healthy baby boy on 24 April at 12.59am here in Singapore and it was life changing moment, managing everything ourselves as our families couldn‚Äôt travel due to the situation..

But

Nothing stopped us from rejoicing and clicking throughout the pregnancy ü§∞ and even later..

My love for theatre, photography, motherhood and high spirits came out together in this photo shoot!

When was the last time you stepped into a wet market? 

My recent trip to a wet market triggered the memories of the good old days doing marketing with my parents. The crowd, the smell, the noise and the hot sticky air somehow were missed. I am so used to getting my stuff from the clean, air conditioned supermarkets now that I actually forgot what its like being in the ‚Äúreal‚Äù market. 

I am going to cut down my trips to the supermarket and go back to the sweet old style. Supporting businesses which i hope will be able to sustain during these trying times. If given a choice, where will you be doing your marketing?

The documentary practice is an impulse to record the order of the day, every day. Occasionally, when it acknowledges the tropes, conventions, symbols, motifs or iconography of an art movement, or when it‚Äôs composition is well-considered (by serendipity or deliberation), it can be treated as a piece of art, or, in exceptional cases, canonised in the traditions of an art movement. This dual treatment of the craft is what keeps me up shooting every day.

Nine Emperor Gods Festival 2020
Leong Nam Temple ÈæçÂçóÊÆø‰πùÁöáÂ§ß‰∫åÂ∏ùÁà∑ÂçÉÁßã
@ East Coast Park

The Nine Emperor Gods Festival is generally held from the last day of the eighth lunar month to the ninth day of the ninth lunar month among Chinese communities in Southeast Asia. 
Devotees believe that the Nine Emperor Gods bestow wealth and longevity on their worshippers. Rituals held during the festival differ among temples in different countries.
It begins with the welcoming procession of the gods from the sea into the temple where they are to be worshipped for nine days, and ends when the gods are sent off procession also via the sea on the ninth day. 

This year the festival has scaled down considerably due to the Covid pandemic. Devotees, however, are still welcome to pray to the dieties but have to observe the social distancing measures in the temples.

Marina Barrage was designed and constructed with green principles and is a showpiece of environmental sustainability. It deservingly won the Green Mark Platinum Infrastructure Award. 

‚ÄãNatural lighting and ventilation eliminates the use for air conditioning and reduces electricity usage. The Green Roof which uses 100% recycled plastics and eco-friendly drainage cells, provides insulation for the rest of the building. Reservoir water is used for cooling the pumps and generators. 
It also has the largest solar park in Singapore.

Am glad to see so many positive changes towards greater emphasis in sustainability in Singapore. Do check out the Sustainable Singapore Gallery while you are there to find out more about sustainability!

One of the major changes that occurred due to the pandemic is the lock down internationally. Doors were literally closed. In many countries, public transport system were shut down as well. 

In Singapore, public transport wasn't shut down completely but there was definitely a decrease in the number of public commuters as people stayed at home. 

Things seem to be improving and we look forward to the opening of doors again!

Singapore is known as a Garden City and Gardens by the Bay truly embodies this. It provides a green space in the city and is designed with conservation and sustainability in mind. 

Rain water collected in the Dragonfly and Kingfisher lakes are cleansed by aquatic plants before being released into the Marina Reservoir. 

Some supertrees have photovoltaic cells to harvest solar energy for lighting while others serve as air exhaust receptacles.

Am encouraged to see so much positive changes towards greater emphasis in conservation and sustainability in Singapore. Let's all play our part!

"The Flight" - by Etienne.
This bronze sculpture depicts a flight of seven birds spreading their wings in formation, rising from water to air. The birds symbolize liberty and peace while the sky carries joy and hope. Each bird is of a different size, with the four larger ones tilting their bodies and providing elegant visual contrast to the three smaller ones above them. This graceful sculpture on a pond exudes a dreamy tranquility amid the bustle of the city.

Part 2 of National Day celebrations: Last night's crowds at Marina Bay

Decided to feature the moment when I realised the fireworks weren't at the usual location and shifted the tripod before stopping bulb shooting to reflect the disappointing dissemination of information and chaotic scenes at marina bay.

No staff around knew where the fireworks were going to be, so crowds split themselves between marina barrage and the usual marina waterfront.

The moment the fireworks started, crowds started rushing over to the narrow strip of marina reservoir. A running crowd is definitely not crowd control. And definitely not safe distancing.

It would have been more practical to clearly announce the location, let those who really wanted to watch space themselves out, and close the area when maximum capacity has been reached.

While it was an impromptu decision for me to drop by marina bay at 8pm, I'm sure many others were there much earlier. It's not nice to make people eager to catch the fireworks wait aimlessly at locations that had no view.

Hopefully, the organisation of future events can have clearer communication so that people know where to go if they wanted to, and can truly share in the joy üá∏üá¨

post_caption:
Congrats @alexgmoments !
You are the final winner of our #madaboutsingapore2020c series.

Maybe this is what‚Äôs good about COVID. It pushed us to realized that we are better than what we thought. We are more capable then we were. We can have more time for family while doing nothing less for work, didn‚Äôt we always ask for work-life balance? We are more productive and efficient now. We realized we don‚Äôt have to spend much on the office tower and maybe we can share the money to people instead. We learned more in the last few months and we know new things. This is not just the new normal, this is the new us.

#MadAboutSingapore2020c was a call for pictures taken from 23rd January 2020 - that's when the first case in Singapore was confirmed. ‚ÄúC‚Äù is an indication of the challenging time of COVID-19 - it is not life as usual. We now recognise that we are living through a major global crisis, which will be remembered for generations to come. As visual storytellers, it is our responsibility to use our passions to document this period as best as we can, that future generations might see and learn ‚Äì and be inspired by the passion and courage of people who lived through this time.

Thanks to @Singapore team for the support, and also to our long term community supporter who has passed a number of Portable LED lights as a gift for this series - although you chose to stay low, you know how much we appreciate your support to this community!

Also big thanks to our judges; @javan, @kcoyco (@tedssingapore), @andy1um, @momentos_sg and @osmioblens - who spent hours every month to go through the entries before hours of judging process via video conference in your precious weekends. The last judging round was a bit emo üò¢

And of course thank you all who have been participating! You have shared encouraging images of how we strive and make it possible to cope with this hard time, and support each other in moving forward. There is no image, no encounter too small or unimportant ‚Äì let‚Äôs continue to build a visual history not just of the big events, but our day-to-day lives as well. 

Let‚Äôs continue to Instagram Singapore!

Chinatown Singapore Mid-Autumn Festival Lightup 2020.
Rain or shine, covid or not, the Mid-Autumn Festival @chinatown_festivals is on.  Kudos to the organisers for lighting up Chinatown to bring some festive cheers to the sombre mood brought about by the pandemic.  Although the hustle and bustle of night markets is missing, lesser crowd allows people to enjoy the colourful lanterns lightup more.  But this friendly Ahmad prefers the colourful Chinese opera.
